{
  "title": "Kale Mushroom Egg Bites",
  "ingredients": [
    "2 tablespoons unsalted butter, divided",
    "5 large leaves fresh kale, stems removed and roughly chopped",
    "3 portobello mushroom caps, cleaned and roughly chopped",
    "1 teaspoon kosher salt, divided",
    "9 large eggs",
    "1/4 cup half and half",
    "Aleppo pepper or smoked paprika, to taste (optional)"
  ],
  "instructions": [
    "Preheat the oven to 325ºF.",
    "Microwave 1 tablespoon of butter in a microwave-safe bowl until melted. Use a brush or paper towel to coat each well of a 12-well muffin tin generously with melted butter.",
    "Using a food processor, pulse the chopped kale for 5-10 seconds, or until shredded into small pieces. Transfer to a bowl and repeat with the chopped portobello mushrooms, pulsing until diced.",
    "Place a large skillet over medium heat and add 1 tablespoon of butter. When the butter is foamy, add the processed mushrooms and 1/4 teaspoon of salt. Sauté for 4-5 minutes, stirring frequently, or until all the liquid from the mushrooms has been released. Add the kale and another 1/4 teaspoon of salt to the skillet and sauté until wilted and tender, about 4-5 minutes more. Remove the skillet from heat and let the vegetables cool slightly.",
    "Using an immersion blender or a regular blender, blend the eggs, half and half, and 1/2 teaspoon of salt until the mixture is frothy and completely combined.",
    "Divide the cooled kale and portobello mushroom mixture among the buttered wells of the muffin tin. Carefully fill each well no more than 3/4 full with the egg mixture. Use a small spoon or butter knife to combine the ingredients in each well, then finish with a sprinkle of smoked paprika or Aleppo pepper on top of each well, if desired.",
    "Bake the egg bites in the preheated oven, rotating the muffin tin halfway through, for 16-19 minutes. When finished, the egg bites will be puffed and barely set in the middle. Test for doneness by poking the center of each egg bite with a fork - they should be bouncy and just set, as they will continue to set up as they cool.",
    "Remove the cooked egg bites from the oven and run a butter knife around the edge of each well to release any stuck-on bits. Let the egg bites cool slightly, then remove them from the tin and serve warm, or allow them to cool to room temperature and store them in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to 5 days."
